messages.content:
So, here's the (first) deck concept as it stands:

**Turn 1:** plays Reinforcement, Delay+, and Taste Blood.
-- Reinforcement is a major part of his defensive ability with this deck, causing his block to scale up over time. Namely, with it, he's always got *at least* as much block as he did 4 rounds ago.
-- Delay+ is also a major part of the deck's defensive power. As long as it's active, all unblocked damage/health loss coming at the boss becomes a Prediction of damage 2 rounds later. (This damage will come in two hits: the first half of it can damage the boss's health directly, but the other half can be delayed again. Either of these hits can be Blocked.)
-- Taste Blood is an attack that will deal 2 damage on round 6, and apply a status effect that will cause the boss to heal as much damage as the prediction applies. This serves to declare *intent* to attack, but doesn't hurt the player yet.)

**Round 2:** Plays Apotheosis+, Delay+, and Death Mark+.
-- We all know what Apotheosis does.
-- I described Delay already. The boss is going to play 2 Delays every 3 rounds, meaning Delay will always be active.
-- Death Mark+ is an attack that inflicts a 2x damage multiplier debuff, and deals 5 damage, but not until round 6, and again on round 8. This increases the round-6 intent to attack, from 1 debuff and 2 damage, to 2 debuffs and 7x2 damage.

**Round 3:** Infinite Pain+, Halflife Period+, and Clumsy.
-- Clumsy is just there to be a one-time thing that won't affect future draws, but still serves as *something* that was drawn this turn.
-- Halflife Period+ creates a prediction in 3 rounds (round 6), based on the target's health. If it's more than half, the boss gains 18 block. Otherwise, it deals 18 damage to the player, while the Death Mark and Taste Blood debuffs are active.
-- Infinite Pain+ is an attack that deals 5 damage on rounds 6 and 8, while also applying a debuff that causes all unblocked damage to happen again after 2 more rounds.
After that, the boss's behavior starts the loop, but the changes in the overall *effects* will last until round 8.

**Round 4 + 3x:** Delay+, Probing Attack+, Counter Strike+
-- Probing Attack+ deals 5 damage after 2 and 4 rounds, while also applying a debuff that causes the boss to gain block equal to the unblocked damage dealt on those turns.
-- Counter Strike: 12 block now, 12 damage in 2 rounds. No associated debuffs.

**Round 5 + 3x:** Delay+, Infinite Pain+, Halflife Period+

**Round 6 + 3x:** Death Mark+, Probing Attack+, Push Time+
-- Push Time+ causes all predictions on a hostile target (the player) to happen 1 round sooner.

I'll admit, it was a long time before I realized that, even though any card you're offered is better than Strike or Defend, there comes a point where adding some cards to your deck *doesn't* increase the quality of the average card in your deck.
(Of course, with mods, it's not necessarily true that any given card will be better than a Strike or Defend.)

In terms of actual damage, this means:
Round 6: at least 29 (x2) damage, plus ITPH
Round 7: at least 25 (x2) damage, plus I**I**PH
Round 9 + 3x: at least 27 (x4) damage, plus IP
Round 10 + 3x: at least 20 (x4) damage, plus IPH

"I" means unblocked damage is also added to the next damage prediction. "I**I**" means that *twice* that much damage is added to the next damage prediction instead.
"T" means unblocked damage heals the boss.
"P" means unblocked damage gives the boss Block.

(x2) means the prediction's damage is doubled unless the player counters the Death Mark debuff with Artifact, and (x4) means the prediction's damage is *quadrupled* unless the player counters the Death Mark debuff with Artifact.
"H" means the base damage (i.e. before the x2/x4 multiplier) is increased by 18 if the player's health is below half. Otherwise, the boss gains 18 block.
Recall that the boss has *at least two* opportunities to apply Block against any incoming attack, and *all* sources of Block, including this one, happen again after 4 rounds.
Based on all that... my brain wants to say that this boss fight should be impossible. But I know, realistically, that it's probably far from it.
